2026-04-16 12:27:45 | INFO     | DiagnosticAssistantLLM | OUTPUT: suggestion_type='hypothesis' action_type=None action_target=None action_description=None suspected_components=['Power supply LED branch wiring', 'Control module LED branches (all 8)', 'Load module lamp branch wiring'] hypothesis_explanation='The latest inspection shows that all problems are confined to the indicator / lamp branches, while the main series path from battery + to battery − remains intact through all switches.\n\nFindings:\n- The PSU green LED anode is not connected to the battery +; only its cathode is tied to the negative output cable. This means the PSU status LED will never light, but this does not affect the series feed to the rest of the chain.\n- All eight control‑module indicator LEDs are physically missing. Their indicator branches are therefore open, so no red LEDs can light, but the main 12 V feed through each module’s switch line is unaffected.\n- In the load module, both the main lamp and the internal indicator lamp have only their negative terminal connected (to the load input −); their positive terminals are floating (no connection to the diode / + line). As a result, even if correct polarity and 12 V are present at the load module, no current can flow through either lamp, so neither can turn on.\n\nBecause the indicator circuits are independent shunt branches, their absence/miswiring does not interrupt the series power path. The single fault that explains the functional symptom “lamp does not turn on with a good battery and all switches ON” is the miswired load module lamps: they are not connected to the positive side at all. Rewiring or replacing the lamp assembly so that each lamp is connected between the diode‑protected + line and the − line will restore lamp operation. The other LED faults only affect indication, not load operation.'
